<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-12-11T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-12-11T04:00:00-05:00" n="501" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d501">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.825/22: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Cunningham</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-12-11T17:00:00+08:00">December 11, 1931—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 11—9:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>I am informed by Japanese colleague compulsory pilotage not in existence
                            in Japan. Possibly an error made in paragraph 5 of my November 24, 2
                                p.m.,<note n="90" xml:id="d501fn90">See telegram No. 1006, November
                                25, 1931, from the Minister in China, <ref target="#pg_594">p.
                                    594</ref>.</note> therefore request that I be informed at
                            earliest possible date whether compulsory pilotage exists by law in
                            principal United States ports for merchant vessels.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to the Legation.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>